summary: This document is a series of email exchanges between the Chambers of Judge Alison J. Nathan and attorneys regarding the case US v. Maxwell (20cr330). The emails discuss the submission of sealed productions, a motion to quash a subpoena, and scheduling for oral argument, indicating active pre-trial proceedings in late November 2021.

persons.name: Alison J. Nathan
persons.context: Presiding judge in the case US v. Maxwell; her chambers are issuing orders and communicating with counsel regarding procedural matters.

events.title: Third Production Submission
events.description: The prosecution submits a third production of materials under temporary seal, made available on an FTP site.

events.title: Second Production Order
events.description: Judge Nathan issues an order related to a second production of materials, to be docketed on Monday.

events.title: Second Production Submission
events.description: The prosecution submits a second production under temporary seal, with FTP credentials sent separately to chambers.

events.title: Production Delivery and Motion Endorsement
events.description: A production cover letter is submitted under seal, and a thumb drive is delivered to the courthouse. Judge Nathan issues a memo endorsement.

events.title: Sealed Letter Submission
events.description: A letter on behalf of a redacted party (M=) is submitted under temporary seal to the court.

events.title: Inquiry on Oral Argument
events.description: Counsel inquires whether the court intends to hear oral argument on a motion to quash at the final pre-trial conference scheduled for the next day.

events.title: Motion to Quash Filed
events.description: The prosecution files a motion to quash the defendant's Rule 17(c) subpoena, submitted under temporary seal with exhibits.

keyFacts: The document shows active pre-trial litigation in US v. Maxwell in late November 2021, with multiple sealed productions being submitted to the court.
A significant motion to quash a defense subpoena (Rule 17(c)) was filed by the prosecution on November 19, 2021, under temporary seal.
The correspondence indicates the use of secure methods for transferring sensitive materials, including FTP sites and password-protected thumb drives delivered to the courthouse.
Judge Alison J. Nathan is actively managing the case, issuing orders and endorsements in response to filings.
The text contains redacted party names (e.g., 'M='), indicating the involvement of individuals or entities whose identities are protected under seal.
